  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions can be traced through several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed historically\n- Initial focus was on concealing proceeds from illegal activities\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First significant anti-money laundering legislation\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Required documentation of large currency transactions\n\n3. International Milestones:\n- 1988 Vienna Convention - First international treaty addressing money laundering\n- Focused on drug trafficking proceeds\n- Established international cooperation framework\n\n4. Key Legislative Expansions:\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - Criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Significantly expanded reporting and enforcement mechanisms\n- Increased scrutiny of financial transactions post-9/11\n\n5. Global Regulatory Framework:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Created international standards for combating money laundering\n- Developed comprehensive recommendations for national regulations\n\n6. Modern Developments:\n- Increasing focus on cryptocurrency and digital transaction laundering\n- Enhanced international cooperation and information sharing\n- More sophisticated detection and prevention technologies\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and global financial practices.",
